John Edward: Language skills essential for world citizens
Scotland's independent schools have a zipper of academic excellence, and it continued in 2018 with another set of excellent exam results, which were reinforced only by individual and collective successes in sports, art, music and other community enterprises.
With over 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Board of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best level of service to their students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for further and higher education, their chosen career, and their position as world citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement a custom school curriculum, we see that world languages continue as a popular and desirable choice of subjects in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to someone in a language he understands, it goes to his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it goes to his heart."
It's a powerful reminder that we can't rely on English only when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From this year’s recent exam results, we can see that languages are at the top of the league tables with the highest success rates in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages received a higher grade A.
The data, collected from SCIS's 74 membership schools showed that 72 percent of students obtained a higher grade A in Mandarins, while 72 percent of those studying German, 69 of those studying French and 63 of those studying Spanish also received an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as vital skills that children and young adults will no doubt need in the future.
Languages now have the same reputation as the STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent schools' curriculum and elsewhere.
A survey by the UK Commission on Professions and Skills found in 2014 that some of the reasons employees provide why they are struggling to fill posts, 17 percent are attributed to a lack of language skills.
Hence, language skills are becoming more and more important to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more likely jobs requiring languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Whatever career a person chooses, if they have learned a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future with such a lifelong skill.
To be able to communicate directly with people from other countries, a multilingual person will automatically be placed above the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation and French was the only language spoken by a double-digit referenced, 15 percent.
That is why investing in today’s children’s language education is now so important.
Knowing several languages, especially those of developing economies, will equip children with a better chance of finding meaningful work.
In Scotland, each school will differ in the languages they teach.
A number of schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while other languages will teach what is considered essential to the UK when looking ahead to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be a number of languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers who are specialists in this field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare and equip children with the skills needed to succeed, regardless of what the future holds.
It cannot be denied at this stage, in a global business environment, that languages are still enormously important to the country's future, and therefore it must be reflected in education.
Truly, modern languages should really be considered "international communication skills."
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity, and excellence to Scotland’s young people.
Il fat bee le faire.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Board of Independent Schools
