North Korea says they'll definitely 'unsure' unilaterally disarmed without confidence.
North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued reductions are aggravating their distrust of the United States and that the country will certainly not give up its nuclear weapons unilaterally without such qualities.
Ri Yong Ho told the world body's annual General Assembly that in the past year North Korea has taken "significant benevolence measures", such as halting nuclear and missile tests, breaking down the nuclear test site and promising not to increase nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"We see, however, no corresponding response from the U.S.," he said.
"Without any confidence in the US, there will be no confidence in our national security, and under such circumstances, we will certainly not disarm ourselves one-sidedly first."
While Ri repeated known North Korean complaints about Washington's resistance to a "phased" approach to the removal of nuclear weapons by which North Korea would be rewarded if it took gradual action, his words seemed significant in that it did not unconditionally reject unilateral removal of nuclear weapons as Pjongjang did in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong-Oen and Donald Trump at the very first summit between a U.S. president and a North Korean leader on June 12 in Singapore when Kim made a commitment to work for the "destruction of nuclear weapons in the Korean Peninsula" while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea's security.
North Korea wants a formal end to the Korean War of 1950-53, but the United States has said that Pjongjang must first give up his nuclear weapons.
Washington also resisted requests to slow down severe international sanctions against North Korea.
"The US insists on the "destruction of nuclear weapons first" and exerts more pressure by intensifying the level of the sanctions to achieve their goal in a compelling way, and even objecting to the 'declaration of the end of the war," said Ri.
"The perception that sanctions can force us on our knees is a dream of the people who are ignorant of us.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions add to our distrust."
Ri said nothing about plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump on which the US leader at the United Nations turned attention earlier in the week.
Rather, the minister drew attention to three meetings during the past five months between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in and added: "If the party in this issue on the destruction of nuclear weapons were South Korea and not the US, the destruction of nuclear weapons in the Korean Peninsula would not have reached such a dead end."
The tone of Ri's speech was still dramaticly different from last year, when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable that North Korea's rockets would be directed to the U.S. land mass after "Mr. Bose President" Trump called Kim a "shipman" on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who threatened to destroy North Korea "fully," praised Kim abundantly for his courage for taking steps to disarm, but he said that much work still needs to be done and that sanctions should remain there until North Korea destroys nuclear weapons.
On Wednesday Trump said he didn't have a time frame for this, and said, "It doesn't matter whether it takes two years, three years, or five months."
China and Russia believe that the UN Security Council should reward Pjongang for the steps they have taken.
But, U.S. Secretary of State, Mike Pompeo, told the UN Security Council Thursday: "Application of sanctions by the Security Council must continue with zeal and without letup until we realize the full, final, confirmed destruction of nuclear weapons."
Since 2006, the Security Council has unanimously intensified sanctions against North Korea in an effort to dry up funding for Pjongjang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met Ri on the outskirts of the UN General Assembly and afterward said that he would visit Pjongjang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo had already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip there had not gone well.
He left Pjongang in July and said that progress had been made, but North Korea accused him just hours later of making " gang-like demands".
North Korea has promised in a meeting with Moon to break down a missile site and also a nuclear complex if the United States takes "corresponding measures".
He said that Kim had told him that the "corresponding measures" he wanted to see are security guarantees that Trump had promised in Singapore as well as steps towards normalizing his relationship with Washington.
Harvard students take a course about enough rest.
A new course at Harvard University this year lets all its pre-graduate students get more sleep in an effort to counteract the growing macho culture of studying by caffeinated 'full-night sessions'.
An academic found that students at the world's top university are often ignorant when it comes to the basic principles of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleeping medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of his kind in the U.S.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a talk about the effect of sleep deprivation on learning.
'At the end of it, one girl approached me and said, 'Why do they tell me now, in my senior year?'
She said that no one had told her how important sleep was--that surprised me,' he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was first presented this year, explains to students the basic principles of how good sleep habits help academically and athletically, as well as how it improves their general well - being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said that after students were found to be seriously deprived of sleep during the week, the university decided to introduce the course.
The hour-long course involves some interactive tasks.
In one department there is a picture of a dormitory, where students should click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise shoes and books to be told about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is influenced by sleep deficiency and the importance of a bedtime routine.
In another department, participants are told how long-term sleep withdrawal can increase risks of heart attacks, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A map of the campus, with interactive icons, then encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
'We know it won't change students' behavior immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know--just as you have the right to know the health effects of choosing to smoke cigarettes,' Prof. Czeisler added.
The culture of pride to 'study all night' still exists, he said, and added that modern technology and ever increasing pressure on students meant that sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
To make sure that you get enough sleep of good quality, a student's 'secret weapon' should be to avoid stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said--even to avoid putting on weight, because sleep deprivation puts the brain in a starvation mode, which makes you feel hungry all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californiar who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after he walked one of his classes last year, during his first year at Harvard.
He said that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to work for a campus-wide course.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar study program before joining the institution where people compete with one another.
Prof. Czeisler recommended that students consider setting an alarm for when to go to sleep, as well as for when to wake up, and to be aware of the harmful effects of 'blue light' emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can disrupt your circadian rhythm and may cause you to struggle to touch the sheep.
