Almanac: Geigerteller’s inventor
And now a page from our "Sunday Morning" almanac: 30 September 1882, today 136 years ago, and OUR TEL VERY OUR ... the day on which future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method to detect and measure radioactivity, an invention that eventually led to the device called the Geiger counter.
Since then the Geiger counter has been a pillar of science, and it has also become a pillar in pop culture, as in the 1950 film "Bels of Coronado," in which those two unlikely cowboy scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans played:
Man: "What on earth is this?"
Rogers: "It's a Geiger counter used to detect radioactive minerals, such as uranium.
When you put on these headphones, you can even hear the effect of the atoms emitted by the radioactivity in the minerals.
Evans: 'Good, it's cracking about now!'
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, just a few days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention bearing his name lives on.
